a-8e4e-4b37-ac37-72e890b0b235\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-19T02:57:02.632Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"646c4cfa-8e4e-4b37-ac37-72e890b0b235\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1\",\"sessionId\":\"6a4bd1ad-5693-4edf-bb54-6c4f535c833f\",\"version\":\"2.1.45\",\"gitBranch\":\"gtrrz-victor/fix-restore-sessions\",\"slug\":\"elegant-toasting-dove\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01PDw4sAjL8WkvZKN57eShYN\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Entire - CLI \\n     2→\\n     3→This repo contains the CLI for Entire.\\n     4→\\n     5→## Architecture\\n     6→\\n     7→- CLI build with github.com/spf13/cobra and github.com/charmbracelet/huh \\n     8→\\n     9→## Key Directories\\n    10→\\n    11→### Commands (`cmd/`)\\n    12→- `entire/`: Main CLI entry point\\n    13→- `entire/cli`: CLI utilities and helpers\\n    14→- `entire/cli/commands`: actual command implementations\\n    15→- `entire/cli/strategy`: strategy implementations - see section below\\n    16→- `entire/cli/checkpoint`: checkpoint storage abstractions (temporary and committed)\\n    17→- `entire/cli/session`: session state management\\n    18→- `entire/cli/integration_test`: integration tests (simulated hooks)\\n    19→- `entire/cli/e2e_test`: E2E tests with real agent calls (see E2E Tests section)\\n    20→\\n    21→## Tech Stack\\n    22→\\n    23→- Language: Go 1.25.x\\n    24→- Build tool: mise, go modules\\n    25→- Linting: golangci-lint\\n    26→\\n    27→## Development\\n    28→\\n    29→### Running Tests\\n    30→```bash\\n    31→mise run test\\n    32→```\\n    33→\\n    34→### Running Integration Tests\\n    35→```bash\\n    36→mise run test:integration\\n    37→```\\n    38→\\n    39→### Running All Tests (CI)\\n    40→```bash\\n    41→mise run test:ci\\n    42→```\\n    43→\\n    44→Integration tests use the `//go:build integration` build tag and are located in `cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/`.\\n    45→\\n    46→### Running E2E Tests (Only When Explicitly Requested)\\n    47→\\n    48→**IMPORTANT: Do NOT run E2E tests proactively.** E2E tests make real API calls to Claude Code, which consume tokens and cost money. Only run them when the user explicitly asks for E2E testing.\\n    49→\\n    50→```bash\\n    51→# Requires Claude Code to be installed and authenticated\\n    52→E2E_AGENT=claude-code go test -tags=e2e ./cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/...\\n    53→\\n    54→# Run a specific test\\n    55→E2E_AGENT=claude-code go test -tags=e2e -run TestE2E_BasicWorkflow ./cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/...\\n    56→```\\n    57→\\n    58→E2E tests:\\n    59→- Use the `//go:build e2e` build tag\\n    60→- Located in `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/`\\n    61→- Test real agent interactions (Claude Code creating files, committing, etc.)\\n    62→- Validate checkpoint scenarios documented in `docs/architecture/checkpoint-scenarios.md`\\n    63→- Support multiple agents via `E2E_AGENT` env var (currently `claude-code`, `gemini-cli` stub)\\n    64→\\n    65→**Environment variables:**\\n    66→- `E2E_AGENT` - Agent to test with (default: `claude-code`)\\n    67→- `E2E_CLAUDE_MODEL` - Claude model to use (default: `haiku` for cost efficiency)\\n    68→- `E2E_TIMEOUT` - Timeout per prompt (default: `2m`)\\n    69→\\n    70→### Test Parallelization\\n    71→\\n    72→**Always use `t.Parallel()` in tests.** Every top-level test function and subtest should call `t.Parallel()` unless it modifies process-global state (e.g., `os.Chdir()`).\\n    73→\\n    74→```go\\n    75→func TestFeature_Foo(t *testing.T) {\\n    76→    t.Parallel()\\n    77→    // ...\\n    78→}\\n    79→\\n    80→// Integration tests: RunForAllStrategies handles t.Parallel() for subtests internally,\\n    81→// but the top-level test still needs it\\n    82→func TestFeature_Bar(t *testing.T) {\\n    83→    t.Parallel()\\n    84→    RunForAllStrategies(t, func(t *testing.T, env *TestEnv, strategyName string) {\\n    85→        // ...\\n    86→    })\\n    87→}\\n    88→```\\n    89→\\n    90→**Exception:** Tests that modify process-global state cannot be parallelized. This includes `os.Chdir()`/`t.Chdir()` and `os.Setenv()`/`t.Setenv()` — Go's test framework will panic if these are used after `t.Parallel()`.\\n    91→\\n    92→### Linting and Formatting\\n    93→```bash\\n    94→mise run fmt && mise run lint\\n    95→```\\n    96→\\n    97→### Before Every Commit (REQUIRED)\\n    98→\\n    99→**CI will fail if you skip these steps:**\\n   100→\\n   101→```bash\\n   102→mise run fmt      # Format code (CI enforces gofmt)\\n   103→mise run lint     # Lint check (CI enforces golangci-lint)\\n   104→mise run test:ci  # Run all tests (unit + integration)\\n   105→```\\n   106→\\n   107→Or combined: `mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test:ci`\\n   108→\\n   109→**Common CI failures from skipping this:**\\n   110→- `gofmt` formatting differences → run `mise run fmt`\\n   111→- Lint errors → run `mise run lint` and fix issues\\n   112→- Test failures → run `mise run test` and fix\\n   113→\\n   114→### Code Duplication Prevention\\n   115→\\n   116→Before implementing Go code, use `/go:discover-related` to find existing utilities and patterns that might be reusable.\\n   117→\\n   118→**Check for duplication:**\\n   119→```bash\\n   120→mise run dup           # Comprehensive check (threshold 50) with summary\\n   121→mise run dup:staged    # Check only staged files\\n   122→mise run lint          # Normal lint includes dupl at threshold 75 (new issues only)\\n   123→mise run lint:full     # All issues at threshold 75\\n   124→```\\n   125→\\n   126→**Tiered thresholds:**\\n   127→- **75 tokens** (lint/CI) - Blocks on serious duplication (~20+ lines)\\n   128→- **50 tokens** (dup) - Advisory, catches smaller patterns (~10+ lines)\\n   129→\\n   130→When duplication is found:\\n   131→1. Check if a helper already exists in `common.go` or nearby utility files\\n   132→2. If not, consider extracting the duplicated logic to a shared helper\\n   133→3. If duplication is intentional (e.g., test setup), add a `//nolint:dupl` comment with explanation\\n   134→\\n   135→## Code Patterns\\n   136→\\n   137→### Error Handling\\n   138→\\n   139→The CLI uses a specific pattern for error output to avoid duplication between Cobra and main.go.\\n   140→\\n   141→**How it works:**\\n   142→- `root.go` sets `SilenceErrors: true` globally - Cobra never prints errors\\n   143→- `main.go` prints errors to stderr, unless the error is a `SilentError`\\n   144→- Commands return `NewSilentError(err)` when they've already printed a custom message\\n   145→\\n   146→**When to use `SilentError`:**\\n   147→Use `NewSilentError()` when you want to print a custom, user-friendly error message instead of the raw error:\\n   148→\\n   149→```go\\n   150→// In a command's RunE function:\\n   151→if _, err := paths.RepoRoot(); err != nil {\\n   152→    cmd.SilenceUsage = true  // Don't show usage for prerequisite errors\\n   153→    fmt.Fprintln(cmd.ErrOrStderr(), \\\"Not a git repository. Please run 'entire enable' from within a git repository.\\\")\\n   154→    return NewSilentError(errors.New(\\\"not a git repository\\\"))\\n   155→}\\n   156→```\\n   157→\\n   158→**When NOT to use `SilentError`:**\\n   159→For normal errors where the default error message is sufficient, just return the error directly. main.go will print it:\\n   160→\\n   161→```go\\n   162→// Normal error - main.go will print \\\"unknown strategy: foo\\\"\\n   163→return fmt.Errorf(\\\"unknown strategy: %s\\\", name)\\n   164→```\\n   165→\\n   166→**Key files:**\\n   167→- `errors.go` - Defines `SilentError` type and `NewSilentError()` constructor\\n   168→- `root.go` - Sets `SilenceErrors: true` on root command\\n   169→- `main.go` - Checks for `SilentError` before printing\\n   170→\\n   171→### Settings\\n   172→\\n   173→All settings access should go through the `settings` package (`cmd/entire/cli/settings/`).\\n   174→\\n   175→**Why a separate package:**\\n   176→The `settings` package exists to avoid import cycles. The `cli` package imports `strategy`, so `strategy` cannot import `cli`. The `settings` package provides shared settings loading that both can use.\\n   177→\\n   178→**Usage:**\\n   179→```go\\n   180→import \\\"github.com/entireio/cli/cmd/entire/cli/settings\\\"\\n   181→\\n   182→// Load full settings object\\n   183→s, err := settings.Load()\\n   184→if err != nil {\\n   185→    // handle error\\n   186→}\\n   187→if s.Enabled {\\n   188→    // ...\\n   189→}\\n   190→\\n   191→// Or use convenience functions\\n   192→if settings.IsSummarizeEnabled() {\\n   193→    // ...\\n   194→}\\n   195→```\\n   196→\\n   197→**Do NOT:**\\n   198→- Read `.entire/settings.json` or `.entire/settings.local.json` directly with `os.ReadFile`\\n   199→- Duplicate settings parsing logic in other packages\\n   200→- Create new settings helpers without adding them to the `settings` package\\n   201→\\n   202→**Key files:**\\n   203→- `settings/settings.go` - `EntireSettings` struct, `Load()`, and helper methods\\n   204→- `config.go` - Higher-level config functions that use settings (for `cli` package consumers)\\n   205→\\n   206→### Logging vs User Output\\n   207→\\n   208→- **Internal/debug logging**: Use `logging.Debug/Info/Warn/Error(ctx, msg, attrs...)` from `cmd/entire/cli/logging/`. Writes to `.entire/logs/`.\\n   209→- **User-facing output**: Use `fmt.Fprint*(cmd.OutOrStdout(), ...)` or `cmd.ErrOrStderr()`.\\n   210→\\n   211→Don't use `fmt.Print*` for operational messages (checkpoint saves, hook invocations, strategy decisions) - those should use the `logging` package.\\n   212→\\n   213→**Privacy**: Don't log user content (prompts, file contents, commit messages). Log only operational metadata (IDs, counts, paths, durations).\\n   214→\\n   215→### Git Operations\\n   216→\\n   217→We use github.com/go-git/go-git for most git operations, but with important exceptions:\\n   218→\\n   219→#### go-git v5 Bugs - Use CLI Instead\\n   220→\\n   221→**Do NOT use go-git v5 for `checkout` or `reset --hard` operations.**\\n   222→\\n   223→go-git v5 has a bug where `worktree.Reset()` with `git.HardReset` and `worktree.Checkout()` incorrectly delete untracked directories even when they're listed in `.gitignore`. This would destroy `.entire/` and `.worktrees/` directories.\\n   224→\\n   225→Use the git CLI instead:\\n   226→```go\\n   227→// WRONG - go-git deletes ignored directories\\n   228→worktree.Reset(&git.ResetOptions{\\n   229→    Commit: hash,\\n   230→    Mode:   git.HardReset,\\n   231→})\\n   232→\\n   233→// CORRECT - use git CLI\\n   234→cmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, \\\"git\\\", \\\"reset\\\", \\\"--hard\\\", hash.String())\\n   235→```\\n   236→\\n   237→See `HardResetWithProtection()` in `common.go` and `CheckoutBranch()` in `git_operations.go` for examples.\\n   238→\\n   239→Regression tests in `hard_reset_test.go` verify this behavior - if go-git v6 fixes this issue, those tests can be used to validate switching back.\\n   240→\\n   241→#### Repo Root vs Current Working Directory\\n   242→\\n   243→**Always use repo root (not `os.Getwd()`) when working with git-relative paths.**\\n   244→\\n   245→Git commands like `git status` and `worktree.Status()` return paths relative to the **repository root**, not the current working directory. When Claude runs from a subdirectory (e.g., `/repo/frontend`), using `os.Getwd()` to construct absolute paths will produce incorrect results for files in sibling directories.\\n   246→\\n   247→```go\\n   248→// WRONG - breaks when running from subdirectory\\n   249→cwd, _ := os.Getwd()  // e.g., /repo/frontend\\n   250→absPath := filepath.Join(cwd, file)  // file=\\\"api/src/types.ts\\\" → /repo/frontend/api/src/types.ts (WRONG)\\n   251→\\n   252→// CORRECT - use repo root\\n   253→repoRoot, _ := paths.RepoRoot()  // or strategy.GetWorktreePath()\\n   254→absPath := filepath.Join(repoRoot, file)  // → /repo/api/src/types.ts (CORRECT)\\n   255→```\\n   256→\\n   257→This also affects path filtering. The `paths.ToRelativePath()` function rejects paths starting with `..`, so computing relative paths from cwd instead of repo root will filter out files in sibling directories:\\n   258→\\n   259→```go\\n   260→// WRONG - filters out sibling directory files\\n   261→cwd, _ := os.Getwd()  // /repo/frontend\\n   262→relPath := paths.ToRelativePath(\\\"/repo/api/file.ts\\\", cwd)  // returns \\\"\\\" (filtered out as \\\"../api/file.ts\\\")\\n   263→\\n   264→// CORRECT - keeps all repo files\\n   265→repoRoot, _ := paths.RepoRoot()\\n   266→relPath := paths.ToRelativePath(\\\"/repo/api/file.ts\\\", repoRoot)  // returns \\\"api/file.ts\\\"\\n   267→```\\n   268→\\n   269→**When to use `os.Getwd()`:** Only when you actually need the current directory (e.g., finding agent session directories that are cwd-relative).\\n   270→\\n   271→**When to use repo root:** Any time you're working with paths from git status, git diff, or any git-relative file list.\\n   272→\\n   273→Test case in `state_test.go`: `TestFilterAndNormalizePaths_SiblingDirectories` documents this bug pattern.\\n   274→\\n   275→### Session Strategies (`cmd/entire/cli/strategy/`)\\n   276→\\n   277→The CLI uses a strategy pattern for managing session data and checkpoints. Each strategy implements the `Strategy` interface defined in `strategy.go`.\\n   278→\\n   279→#### Core Interface\\n   280→All strategies implement:\\n   281→- `SaveStep()` - Save session step checkpoint (code + metadata)\\n   282→- `SaveTaskStep()` - Save subagent task step checkpoint\\n   283→- `GetRewindPoints()` / `Rewind()` - List and restore to checkpoints\\n   284→- `GetSessionLog()` / `GetSessionInfo()` - Retrieve session data\\n   285→- `ListSessions()` / `GetSession()` - Session discovery\\n   286→\\n   287→#### Available Strategies\\n   288→\\n   289→| Strategy | Main Branch | Metadata Storage | Use Case |\\n   290→|----------|-------------|------------------|----------|\\n   291→| **manual-commit** (default) | Unchanged (no commits) | `entire/<HEAD-hash>-<worktreeHash>` branches + `entire/checkpoints/v1` | Recommended for most workflows |\\n   292→| **auto-commit** | Creates clean commits | Orphan `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch | Teams that want code commits from sessions |\\n   293→\\n   294→#### Strategy Details\\n   295→\\n   296→**Manual-Commit Strategy** (`manual_commit*.go`) - Default\\n   297→- **Does not modify** the active branch - no commits created on the working branch\\n   298→- Creates shadow branch `entire/<HEAD-commit-hash[:7]>-<worktreeHash[:6]>` per base commit + worktree\\n   299→- **Worktree-specific branches** - each git worktree gets its own shadow branch namespace, preventing conflicts\\n   300→- **Supports multiple concurrent sessions** - checkpoints from different sessions in the same directory interleave on the same shadow branch\\n   301→- Session logs are condensed to permanent `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch on user commits\\n   302→- Builds git trees in-memory using go-git plumbing APIs\\n   303→- Rewind restores files from shadow branch commit tree (does not use `git reset`)\\n   304→- Tracks session state in `.git/entire-sessions/` (shared across worktrees)\\n   305→- **Shadow branch migration** - if user does stash/pull/rebase (HEAD changes without commit), shadow branch is automatically moved to new base commit\\n   306→- **Orphaned branch cleanup** - if a shadow branch exists without a corresponding session state file, it is automatically reset when a new session starts\\n   307→- PrePush hook can push `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch alongside user pushes\\n   308→- `AllowsMainBranch() = true` - safe to use on main/master since it never modifies commit history\\n   309→\\n   310→**Auto-Commit Strategy** (`auto_commit.go`)\\n   311→- Code commits to active branch with **clean history** (commits have `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer only)\\n   312→- Metadata stored on orphan `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch at sharded paths: `<id[:2]>/<id[2:]>/`\\n   313→- Uses `checkpoint.WriteCommitted()` for metadata storage\\n   314→- Checkpoint ID (12-hex-char) links code commits to metadata on `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n   315→- Full rewind allowed if commit is only on current branch (not in main); otherwise logs-only\\n   316→- Rewind via `git reset --hard`\\n   317→- PrePush hook can push `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch alongside user pushes\\n   318→- `AllowsMainBranch() = true` - creates commits on active branch, safe to use on main/master\\n   319→\\n   320→#### Key Files\\n   321→\\n   322→- `strategy.go` - Interface definition and context structs (`StepContext`, `TaskStepContext`, `RewindPoint`, etc.)\\n   323→- `registry.go` - Strategy registration/discovery (factory pattern with `Get()`, `List()`, `Default()`)\\n   324→- `common.go` - Shared helpers for metadata extraction, tree building, rewind validation, `ListCheckpoints()`\\n   325→- `session.go` - Session/checkpoint data structures\\n   326→- `push_common.go` - Shared PrePush logic for pushing `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch\\n   327→- `manual_commit.go` - Manual-commit strategy main implementation\\n   328→- `manual_commit_types.go` - Type definitions: `SessionState`, `CheckpointInfo`, `CondenseResult`\\n   329→- `manual_commit_session.go` - Session state management (load/save/list session states)\\n   330→- `manual_commit_condensation.go` - Condense logic for copying logs to `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n   331→- `manual_commit_rewind.go` - Rewind implementation: file restoration from checkpoint trees\\n   332→- `manual_commit_git.go` - Git operations: checkpoint commits, tree building\\n   333→- `manual_commit_logs.go` - Session log retrieval and session listing\\n   334→- `manual_commit_hooks.go` - Git hook handlers (prepare-commit-msg, post-commit, pre-push)\\n   335→- `manual_commit_reset.go` - Shadow branch reset/cleanup functionality\\n   336→- `session_state.go` - Package-level session state functions (`LoadSessionState`, `SaveSessionState`, `ListSessionStates`, `FindMostRecentSession`)\\n   337→- `auto_commit.go` - Auto-commit strategy implementation\\n   338→- `hooks.go` - Git hook installation\\n   339→\\n   340→#### Checkpoint Package (`cmd/entire/cli/checkpoint/`)\\n   341→- `checkpoint.go` - Data types (`Checkpoint`, `TemporaryCheckpoint`, `CommittedCheckpoint`)\\n   342→- `store.go` - `GitStore` struct wrapping git repository\\n   343→- `temporary.go` - Shadow branch operations (`WriteTemporary`, `ReadTemporary`, `ListTemporary`)\\n   344→- `committed.go` - Metadata branch operations (`WriteCommitted`, `ReadCommitted`, `ListCommitted`)\\n   345→\\n   346→#### Session Package (`cmd/entire/cli/session/`)\\n   347→- `session.go` - Session data types and interfaces\\n   348→- `state.go` - `StateStore` for managing `.git/entire-sessions/` files\\n   349→- `phase.go` - Session phase state machine (phases, events, transitions, actions)\\n   350→\\n   351→#### Session Phase State Machine\\n   352→\\n   353→Sessions track their lifecycle through phases managed by a state machine in `session/phase.go`:\\n   354→\\n   355→**Phases:** `ACTIVE`, `IDLE`, `ENDED`\\n   356→\\n   357→**Events:**\\n   358→- `TurnStart` - Agent begins a turn (UserPromptSubmit hook)\\n   359→- `TurnEnd` - Agent finishes a turn (Stop hook)\\n   360→- `GitCommit` - A git commit was made (PostCommit hook)\\n   361→- `SessionStart` - New session started\\n   362→- `SessionStop` - Session explicitly stopped\\n   363→\\n   364→**Key transitions:**\\n   365→- `IDLE + TurnStart → ACTIVE` - Agent starts working\\n   366→- `ACTIVE + TurnEnd → IDLE` - Agent finishes turn\\n   367→- `ACTIVE + GitCommit → ACTIVE` - User commits while agent is working (condense immediately)\\n   368→- `IDLE + GitCommit → IDLE` - User commits between turns (condense immediately)\\n   369→- `ENDED + GitCommit → ENDED` - Post-session commit (condense if files touched)\\n   370→\\n   371→The state machine emits **actions** (e.g., `ActionCondense`, `ActionUpdateLastInteraction`) that hook handlers dispatch to strategy-specific implementations.\\n   372→\\n   373→#### Metadata Structure\\n   374→\\n   375→**Shadow Strategy** - Shadow branches (`entire/<commit-hash[:7]>-<worktreeHash[:6]>`):\\n   376→```\\n   377→.entire/metadata/<session-id>/\\n   378→├── full.jsonl               # Session transcript\\n   379→├── prompt.txt               # User prompts\\n   380→├── context.md               # Generated context\\n   381→└── tasks/<tool-use-id>/     # Task checkpoints\\n   382→    ├── checkpoint.json      # UUID mapping for rewind\\n   383→    └── agent-<id>.jsonl     # Subagent transcript\\n   384→```\\n   385→\\n   386→**Both Strategies** - Metadata branch (`entire/checkpoints/v1`) - sharded checkpoint format:\\n   387→```\\n   388→<checkpoint-id[:2]>/<checkpoint-id[2:]>/\\n   389→├── metadata.json            # CheckpointSummary (aggregated stats)\\n   390→├── 0/                       # First session (0-based indexing)\\n   391→│   ├── metadata.json        # Session-specific metadata\\n   392→│   ├── full.jsonl           # Session transcript\\n   393→│   ├── prompt.txt           # User prompts\\n   394→│   ├── context.md           # Generated context\\n   395→│   ├── content_hash.txt     # SHA256 of transcript\\n   396→│   └── tasks/<tool-use-id>/ # Task checkpoints (if applicable)\\n   397→│       ├── checkpoint.json  # UUID mapping\\n   398→│       └── agent-<id>.jsonl # Subagent transcript\\n   399→├── 1/                       # Second session (if multiple sessions)\\n   400→│   ├── metadata.json\\n   401→│   ├── full.jsonl\\n   402→│   └── ...\\n   403→└── ...\\n   404→```\\n   405→\\n   406→**Multi-session metadata.json format:**\\n   407→```json\\n   408→{\\n   409→  \\\"checkpoint_id\\\": \\\"abc123def456\\\",\\n   410→  \\\"session_id\\\": \\\"2026-01-13-uuid\\\",      // Current/latest session\\n   411→  \\\"session_ids\\\": [\\\"2026-01-13-uuid1\\\", \\\"2026-01-13-uuid2\\\"],  // All sessions\\n   412→  \\\"session_count\\\": 2,                    // Number of sessions in this checkpoint\\n   413→  \\\"strategy\\\": \\\"manual-commit\\\",\\n   414→  \\\"created_at\\\": \\\"2026-01-13T12:00:00Z\\\",\\n   415→  \\\"files_touched\\\": [\\\"file1.txt\\\", \\\"file2.txt\\\"]  // Merged from all sessions\\n   416→}\\n   417→```\\n   418→\\n   419→When multiple sessions are condensed to the same checkpoint (same base commit):\\n   420→- Sessions are stored in numbered subfolders using 0-based indexing (`0/`, `1/`, `2/`, etc.)\\n   421→- Latest session is always in the highest-numbered folder\\n   422→- `session_ids` array tracks all sessions, `session_count` increments\\n   423→\\n   424→**Session State** (filesystem, `.git/entire-sessions/`):\\n   425→```\\n   426→<session-id>.json            # Active session state (base_commit, checkpoint_count, etc.)\\n   427→```\\n   428→\\n   429→#### Checkpoint ID Linking\\n   430→\\n   431→Both strategies use a **12-hex-char random checkpoint ID** (e.g., `a3b2c4d5e6f7`) as the stable identifier linking user commits to metadata.\\n   432→\\n   433→**How checkpoint IDs work:**\\n   434→\\n   435→1. **Generated once per checkpoint**: Either when saving (auto-commit) or when condensing (manual-commit)\\n   436→\\n   437→2. **Added to user commits** via `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer:\\n   438→   - **Auto-commit**: Added programmatically when creating the commit\\n   439→   - **Manual-commit**: Added via `prepare-commit-msg` hook (user can remove it before committing)\\n   440→\\n   441→3. **Used for directory sharding** on `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch:\\n   442→   - Path format: `<id[:2]>/<id[2:]>/`\\n   443→   - Example: `a3b2c4d5e6f7` → `a3/b2c4d5e6f7/`\\n   444→   - Creates 256 shards to avoid directory bloat\\n   445→\\n   446→4. **Appears in commit subject** on `entire/checkpoints/v1` commits:\\n   447→   - Format: `Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7`\\n   448→   - Makes `git log entire/checkpoints/v1` readable and searchable\\n   449→\\n   450→**Bidirectional linking:**\\n   451→\\n   452→```\\n   453→User commit → Metadata:\\n   454→  Extract \\\"Entire-Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\" trailer\\n   455→  → Read a3/b2c4d5e6f7/ directory from entire/checkpoints/v1 tree at HEAD\\n   456→\\n   457→Metadata → User commits:\\n   458→  Given checkpoint ID a3b2c4d5e6f7\\n   459→  → Search user branch history for commits with \\\"Entire-Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\" trailer\\n   460→```\\n   461→\\n   462→Note: Commit subjects on `entire/checkpoints/v1` (e.g., `Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7`) are\\n   463→for human readability in `git log` only. The CLI always reads from the tree at HEAD.\\n   464→\\n   465→**Example:**\\n   466→```\\n   467→User's commit (on main branch):\\n   468→  \\\"Implement login feature\\n   469→\\n   470→  Entire-Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\"\\n   471→       ↓ ↑\\n   472→       Linked via checkpoint ID\\n   473→       ↓ ↑\\n   474→entire/checkpoints/v1 commit:\\n   475→  Subject: \\\"Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\"\\n   476→\\n   477→  Tree: a3/b2c4d5e6f7/\\n   478→    ├── metadata.json (checkpoint_id: \\\"a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\")\\n   479→    ├── full.jsonl (session transcript)\\n   480→    ├── prompt.txt\\n   481→    └── context.md\\n   482→```\\n   483→\\n   484→#### Commit Trailers\\n   485→\\n   486→**On user's active branch commits (both strategies):**\\n   487→- `Entire-Checkpoint: <checkpoint-id>` - 12-hex-char ID linking to metadata on `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n   488→  - Auto-commit: Always added when creating commits\\n   489→  - Manual-commit: Added by hook; user can remove to skip linking\\n   490→\\n   491→**On shadow branch commits (`entire/<commit-hash[:7]>-<worktreeHash[:6]>`) - manual-commit only:**\\n   492→- `Entire-Session: <session-id>` - Session identifier\\n   493→- `Entire-Metadata: <path>` - Path to metadata directory within the tree\\n   494→- `Entire-Task-Metadata: <path>` - Path to task metadata directory (for task checkpoints)\\n   495→- `Entire-Strategy: manual-commit` - Strategy that created the commit\\n   496→\\n   497→**On metadata branch commits (`entire/checkpoints/v1`) - both strategies:**\\n   498→\\n   499→Commit subject: `Checkpoint: <checkpoint-id>` (or custom subject for task checkpoints)\\n   500→\\n   501→Trailers:\\n   502→- `Entire-Session: <session-id>` - Session identifier\\n   503→- `Entire-Strategy: <strategy>` - Strategy name (manual-commit or auto-commit)\\n   504→- `Entire-Agent: <agent-name>` - Agent name (optional, e.g., \\\"Claude Code\\\")\\n   505→- `Ephemeral-branch: <branch>` - Shadow branch name (optional, manual-commit only)\\n   506→- `Entire-Metadata-Task: <path>` - Task metadata path (optional, for task checkpoints)\\n   507→\\n   508→**Note:** Both strategies keep active branch history **clean** - the only addition to user commits is the single `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer. Manual-commit never creates commits on the active branch (user creates them manually). Auto-commit creates commits but only adds the checkpoint trailer. All detailed session data (transcripts, prompts, context) is stored on the `entire/checkpoints/v1` orphan branch or shadow branches.\\n   509→\\n   510→#### Multi-Session Behavior\\n   511→\\n   512→**Concurrent Sessions:**\\n   513→- When a second session starts in the same directory while another has uncommitted checkpoints, a warning is shown\\n   514→- Both sessions can proceed - their checkpoints interleave on the same shadow branch\\n   515→- Each session's `RewindPoint` includes `SessionID` and `SessionPrompt` to help identify which checkpoint belongs to which session\\n   516→- On commit, all sessions are condensed together with archived sessions in numbered subfolders\\n   517→- Note: Different git worktrees have separate shadow branches (worktree-specific naming), so concurrent sessions in different worktrees do not conflict\\n   518→\\n   519→**Orphaned Shadow Branches:**\\n   520→- A shadow branch is \\\"orphaned\\\" if it exists but has no corresponding session state file\\n   521→- This can happen if the state file is manually deleted or lost\\n   522→- When a new session starts with an orphaned branch, the branch is automatically reset\\n   523→- If the existing session DOES have a state file (concurrent session in same directory), a `SessionIDConflictError` is returned\\n   524→\\n   525→**Shadow Branch Migration (Pull/Rebase):**\\n   526→- If user does stash → pull → apply (or rebase), HEAD changes but work isn't committed\\n   527→- The shadow branch would be orphaned at the old commit\\n   528→- Detection: base commit changed AND old shadow branch still exists (would be deleted if user committed)\\n   529→- Action: shadow branch is renamed from `entire/<old-hash>-<worktreeHash>` to `entire/<new-hash>-<worktreeHash>`\\n   530→- Session continues seamlessly with checkpoints preserved\\n   531→\\n   532→#### When Modifying Strategies\\n   533→- All strategies must implement the full `Strategy` interface\\n   534→- Register new strategies in `init()` using `Register()`\\n   535→- Test with `mise run test` - strategy tests are in `*_test.go` files\\n   536→- **Update this CLAUDE.md** when adding or modifying strategies to keep documentation current\\n   537→\\n   538→# Important Notes\\n   539→\\n   540→- **Before committing:** Follow the \\\"Before Every Commit (REQUIRED)\\\" checklist above - CI will fail without it\\n   541→- Integration tests: run `mise run test:integration` when changing integration test code\\n   542→- When adding new features, ensure they are well-tested and documented.\\n   543→- Always check for code duplication and refactor as needed.\\n   544→\\n   545→## Go Code Style\\n   546→- Write lint-compliant Go code on the first attempt. Before outputting Go code, mentally verify it passes `golangci-lint` (or your specific linter).\\n   547→- Follow standard Go idioms: proper error handling, no unused variables/imports, correct formatting (gofmt), meaningful names.\\n   548→- Handle all errors explicitly—don't leave them unchecked.\\n   549→- Reference `.golangci.yml` for enabled linters before writing Go code.\\n   550→\\n   551→## Accessibility\\n   552→\\n   553→The CLI supports an accessibility mode for users who rely on screen readers. This mode uses simpler text prompts instead of interactive TUI elements.\\n   554→\\n   555→### Environment Variable\\n   556→- `ACCESSIBLE=1` (or any non-empty value) enables accessibility mode\\n   557→- Users can set this in their shell profile (`.bashrc`, `.zshrc`) for persistent use\\n   558→\\n   559→### Implementation Guidelines\\n   560→\\n   561→When adding new interactive forms or prompts using `huh`:\\n   562→\\n   563→**In the `cli` package:**\\n   564→Use `NewAccessibleForm()` instead of `huh.NewForm()`:\\n   565→```go\\n   566→// Good - respects ACCESSIBLE env var\\n   567→form := NewAccessibleForm(\\n   568→    huh.NewGroup(\\n   569→        huh.NewSelect[string]().\\n   570→            Title(\\\"Choose an option\\\").\\n   571→            Options(...).\\n   572→            Value(&choice),\\n   573→    ),\\n   574→)\\n   575→\\n   576→// Bad - ignores accessibility setting\\n   577→form := huh.NewForm(...)\\n   578→```\\n   579→\\n   580→**In the `strategy` package:**\\n   581→Use the `isAccessibleMode()` helper. Note that `WithAccessible()` is only available on forms, not individual fields, so wrap confirmations in a form:\\n   582→```go\\n   583→form := huh.NewForm(\\n   584→    huh.NewGroup(\\n   585→        huh.NewConfirm().\\n   586→            Title(\\\"Confirm action?\\\").\\n   587→            Value(&confirmed),\\n   588→    ),\\n   589→)\\n   590→if isAccessibleMode() {\\n   591→    form = form.WithAccessible(true)\\n   592→}\\n   593→if err := form.Run(); err != nil { ... }\\n   594→```\\n   595→\\n   596→### Key Points\\n   597→- Always use the accessibility hel