 is that the fallback now generates a filename containing `time.Now()`. When no existing session file is found (i.e., the session file doesn't yet exist at the new location), the fallback is called twice (once in `classifySessionsForRestore` to check timestamps, then once in `RestoreLogsOnly` to actually write) and will produce **two different filenames** because `time.Now()` differs between calls. Even if called in the same second, the path returned on read will differ from the path used on write if the minute boundary is crossed.\\n\\nFurthermore, on cross-machine restore (the stated use case), there is no existing Gemini session file at the target location, so the `filepath.Glob` will never find a match. The fallback always fires, and every call to `ResolveSessionFile` for the same session ID will return a different path whenever the minute changes.\\n\\nThe old fallback `filepath.Join(sessionDir, agentSessionID+\\\".json\\\")` was deterministic. The new fallback is not. This violates the implicit contract that `ResolveSessionFile` is a pure path resolver: the same inputs should produce the same output. The doc comment on the function says nothing about time-based filenames in the fallback.\\n\\nAdditionally, the test for the fallback (in `gemini_test.go`) only checks that the prefix and suffix match — it doesn't test for determinism across multiple calls, which would catch this bug.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issue 2: `NOTE` comment in `rewind.go` about task checkpoint transcript format is still accurate — no violation, but worth flagging\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/cmd/entire/cli/rewind.go`, lines 733–738:\\n```go\\n// NOTE: The transcript parsing/truncation/writing pipeline (transcript.ParseFromBytes,\\n// TruncateTranscriptAtUUID, writeTranscript) assumes Claude's JSONL format.\\n// This is acceptable because task checkpoints are currently only created by Claude Code's\\n// PostToolUse hook. If other agents gain sub-agent support, this will need a\\n// format-aware refactor (agent-specific parsing, truncation, and serialization).\\n```\\n\\nThe PR moves `resolveTranscriptPath` from `rewind.go` to `transcript.go` but leaves its usage within `rewind.go` unchanged. The `restoreTaskCheckpointTranscript` function still calls `resolveTranscriptPath` (line 755), and the NOTE is still valid. No violation here — just confirming that the NOTE still stands and is undisturbed.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issue 3: `ResolveSessionFilePath` doc comment described a fallback to session state; that function was removed without verifying all callers are correct\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/cmd/entire/cli/strategy/manual_commit_rewind.go`\\n\\nThe removed `ResolveSessionFilePath` had this doc comment:\\n```go\\n// ResolveSessionFilePath determines the correct file path for an agent's session transcript.\\n// Checks session state for transcript_path first (needed for agents like Gemini that store\\n// transcripts at paths that GetSessionDir can't reconstruct, e.g. SHA-256 hashed directories).\\n// Falls back to the agent's ExtractAgentSessionID + ResolveSessionFile with fallbackSessionDir.\\n```\\n\\nThe PR removes this function and replaces it with direct calls to `agent.ResolveSessionFile`. The comment explains this was specifically needed for \\\"agents like Gemini that store transcripts at paths that **GetSessionDir can't reconstruct**, e.g. SHA-256 hashed directories.\\\"\\n\\nThe PR's own replacement comment says:\\n> \\\"Use agent.ResolveSessionFile directly (not ResolveSessionFilePath) because ResolveSessionFilePath reads .git/entire-sessions/ state which may contain stale absolute paths from the original repo location.\\\"\\n\\nThis is correct for the location-independence goal, **but the original concern is now addressed by the `GetProjectHash` change** — `GetSessionDir` now correctly reconstructs the SHA-256 hashed Gemini directory from the current repo path. So this is self-consistent. However, the correctness of this depends entirely on `GetProjectHash` producing the same hash as Gemini CLI's internal `getProjectHash()`. The PR's comment in `GetProjectHash` says it \\\"matches Gemini CLI's getProjectHash() which uses SHA256 of the project root\\\" — but there is no test verifying that the hash value matches what Gemini CLI actually produces for a real path. This is an assumption that could silently fail if Gemini CLI changes its implementation or uses a different input format.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issue 4: `SessionTranscriptPath` / `TranscriptPath` removal — potential backward-compatibility concern with `CommittedMetadata`\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/cmd/entire/cli/checkpoint/checkpoint.go`\\n\\nThe removed field had a comment:\\n```go\\n// TranscriptPath is the home-relative path to the session transcript file.\\n// Persisted so restore can write the transcript back to the correct location\\n// without needing to reconstruct agent-specific paths (e.g. SHA-256 hashed dirs for Gemini).\\n```\\n\\n`TranscriptPath` was a JSON field (`json:\\\"transcript_path,omitempty\\\"`) on `CommittedMetadata`. Removing it from the struct means **existing committed checkpoints that already have `transcript_path` written to git will have that field silently ignored** when deserialized. That's fine from a Go JSON perspective (unknown fields are ignored), but any checkpoints written by an older CLI version that relied on this field for restore will now silently fall back to the computed path — which may produce a different result if the Gemini hash implementation differs from the old path-sanitization approach.\\n\\nThis is a behavioral change for users who have old checkpoints, but it's intentional and the PR explains why (location independence). No comment guidance is technically violated, but the `// Persisted so restore can write the transcript back to the correct location` comment's rationale is being discarded in favor of a different approach. This is acceptable if the new approach works.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Summary of Issues\\n\\n**Critical:**\\n\\n1. **`ResolveSessionFile` fallback is non-deterministic.** The new fallback uses `time.Now()` to construct the filename, meaning two calls for the same session ID at different times (or across a minute boundary) return different paths. This breaks the `classifySessionsForRestore` → `RestoreLogsOnly` pipeline, which calls `ResolveSessionFile` twice for the same session: once to check if the local file is newer (classify), and once to write the transcript. If the minute changes between those calls, the file is written to a path that was never checked, and the \\\"already up to date\\\" check is bypassed. The previous fallback (`agentSessionID+\\\".json\\\"`) was deterministic.\\n\\n**Moderate:**\\n\\n2. **`GetProjectHash` correctness is untested against real Gemini CLI behavior.** The hash must exactly match Gemini CLI's `getProjectHash()` output for the session directory to be found. There is no integration test or reference value test that validates the SHA256 input format matches what Gemini actually uses. If Gemini passes a normalized/canonicalized path (e.g., resolving symlinks, trailing slashes) rather than the raw string, the hashes would differ and `GetSessionDir` would return the wrong directory.\"},{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"agentId: ab6aafd (for resuming to continue this agent's work if needed)\\n<usage>total_tokens: 145974\\ntool_uses: 13\\nduration_ms: 76377</usage>\"}]}]},\"uuid\":\"7ecc8bff-30b1-498b-8ee0-cdb4f8e62f0b\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-19T02:58:37.212Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"status\":\"completed\",\"prompt\":\"You are reviewing PR #403 (\\\"fix: restore sessions\\\") on the entireio/cli repo. Check that the changes comply with any guidance in code comments in the modified files.\\n\\nFirst get the file list:\\n```\\ngh pr diff 403 --name-only\\n```\\n\\nThen read the FULL content of each modified file (not just the diff):\\n- cmd/entire/cl