e.\\n\\nReturn any relevant findings. If nothing relevant, say so.\\n\\nWorking directory: /Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1\",\"agentId\":\"a2af03e\"},\"toolUseID\":\"agent_msg_01MsnRkVZGyZUbksJfsDVs9B\",\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01TvihqXLPfzVXtwVKV9U73y\",\"uuid\":\"715a36ba-a552-48b5-b1bb-3f10eb65a7af\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-19T03:13:35.584Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"715a36ba-a552-48b5-b1bb-3f10eb65a7af\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1\",\"sessionId\":\"6a4bd1ad-5693-4edf-bb54-6c4f535c833f\",\"version\":\"2.1.45\",\"gitBranch\":\"gtrrz-victor/fix-restore-sessions\",\"slug\":\"elegant-toasting-dove\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"PostToolUse\",\"hookName\":\"PostToolUse:Task\",\"command\":\"go run ${CLAUDE_PROJECT_DIR}/cmd/entire/main.go hooks claude-code post-task\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01EtxYA4W4Fn8LQdeCAMULp2\",\"toolUseID\":\"toolu_01EtxYA4W4Fn8LQdeCAMULp2\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-19T03:13:54.737Z\",\"uuid\":\"20dbe4ec-4fa9-499d-8d34-78ac706d11ec\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"ad09dd36-3624-433c-be3b-29a1f9409a96\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1\",\"sessionId\":\"6a4bd1ad-5693-4edf-bb54-6c4f535c833f\",\"version\":\"2.1.45\",\"gitBranch\":\"gtrrz-victor/fix-restore-sessions\",\"slug\":\"elegant-toasting-dove\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01EtxYA4W4Fn8LQdeCAMULp2\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"Now I have all the information needed. Here is my comprehensive review:\\n\\n---\\n\\n## PR #403 Review: Issues Found from Git History\\n\\n### Issue 1: Breaking Change for Existing Gemini Users — `SanitizePathForGemini` → `GetProjectHash` (SHA256)\\n\\n**Severity: High**\\n\\n**What changed:** The PR replaces `SanitizePathForGemini` (replace non-alphanumeric chars with `-`) with `GetProjectHash` (SHA256 of the path). This changes the directory Gemini session files are looked up in.\\n\\n**Git history context:** The `SanitizePathForGemini` function was introduced in commit `990d1673` (\\\"Add Gemini CLI integration for session tracking with entire\\\") as the initial implementation of Gemini's project directory hashing. It was documented as \\\"a hash-like sanitization similar to Claude.\\\" The PR correctly identifies it was wrong — Gemini's actual source code at `/opt/homebrew/Cellar/gemini-cli/0.28.2/libexec/lib/node_modules/@google/gemini-cli/node_modules/@google/gemini-cli-core/dist/src/config/storage.js` confirms:\\n\\n```javascript\\ngetFilePathHash(filePath) {\\n    return crypto.createHash('sha256').update(filePath).digest('hex');\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**The real risk:** Any Gemini user who ran a session with the old `SanitizePathForGemini` code will have their session files stored at `~/.gemini/tmp/<sanitized-path>/chats/` (e.g., `~/.gemini/tmp/-Users-alice-project/chats/`). After this PR, the tool will look in `~/.gemini/tmp/<sha256>/chats/`. **The old session files will not be found.** This is a forward fix but silently breaks backward lookup of sessions stored before this fix.\\n\\nThe PR itself will not find sessions stored by the old code on existing installations. The `ResolveSessionFile` glob fallback (`session-*-<id[:8]>.json`) mitigates this *within a session* if the directory is correct, but with the wrong directory entirely, no glob will match.\\n\\n**Question to ask:** Were any Gemini users using the broken `SanitizePathForGemini` path in production before this PR? If so, their historical sessions are unreachable.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issue 2: Stale Comment in `transcript.go`\\n\\n**Severity: Low (comment only)**\\n\\nThe comment at `/Users/alex/workspace/cli/.worktrees/1/cmd/entire/cli/transcript.go:262` says:\\n\\n```go\\n// resolveTranscriptPath determines the correct file path for an agent's session transcript.\\n// Delegates to strategy.ResolveSessionFilePath after computing the fallback session directory.\\n```\\n\\nBut `ResolveSessionFilePath` was deleted by this PR. The function now calls `agent.ResolveSessionFile` directly. The comment is now inaccurate and was moved from `rewind.go` (where it was accurately describing the old behavior) without being updated.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issue 3: `TranscriptPath` Field Fully Removed vs. Prior Commit's Deprecation-Only Approach\\n\\n**Severity: Medium — backward compatibility concern**\\n\\nThe immediately preceding commit `91b70575` (\\\"fix: remove stored transcript path from checkpoint metadata for location independence\\\") deliberately kept the `SessionTranscriptPath` and `TranscriptPath` fields with \\\"DEPRECATED\\\" documentation and `json:\\\"transcript_path,omitempty\\\"` tags, explicitly to maintain backward compatibility with old checkpoints. Quoting that commit's message:\\n\\n> \\\"Add deprecation comments (checkpoint.go) — Mark TranscriptPath fields as DEPRECATED. Keep for backward compatibility with old checkpoints.\\\"\\n\\nThis PR fully removes those fields from both `WriteCommittedOptions` and `CommittedMetadata`. The JSON field removal (`json:\\\"transcript_path,omitempty\\\"`) means:\\n\\n- **Reading old checkpoints:** Safe — Go JSON unmarshaling silently ignores unknown fields. Old checkpoints with `transcript_path` in their JSON will deserialize without error; the field is just dropped.\\n- **Struct usage:** Any call site that previously set `SessionTranscriptPath` will now fail to compile (intentionally, since `manual_commit_condensation.go` already stopped writing it in `91b70575`). This is fine.\\n\\nHowever, the previous commit's explicit architectural decision was to keep these fields around for one version cycle to signal intent. This PR removes them in the very next commit — same PR series — which compresses what was intended to be a phased deprecation. This seems intentional but deviates from the comment written two days earlier.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issue 4: `ResolveSessionFilePath` Deleted but Its `LoadSessionState` Logic Not Replaced\\n\\n**Severity: Medium**\\n\\nThe old `ResolveSessionFilePath` function (deleted in commit `19aa9184`) contained this logic:\\n\\n```go\\nfunc ResolveSessionFilePath(sessionID string, ag agent.Agent, fallbackSessionDir string) string {\\n    state, err := LoadSessionState(sessionID)\\n    if err == nil && state != nil && state.TranscriptPath != \\\"\\\" {\\n        return state.TranscriptPath  // Use stored absolute path from session state\\n    }\\n    return ag.ResolveSessionFile(fallbackSessionDir, sessionID)\\n}\\n```\\n\\nThe session state (`LoadSessionState`) stores a `TranscriptPath` in `.git/entire-sessions/<session-id>.json`. This was the live, correct absolute path written when the session was active. The PR comments in `manual_commit_rewind.go` (lines 709-711) justify the removal:\\n\\n```\\n// Use agent.ResolveSessionFile directly (not ResolveSessionFilePath) because\\n// ResolveSessionFilePath reads .git/entire-sessions/ state which may contain\\n// stale absolute paths from the original repo location.\\n```\\n\\n**The subtle regression:** For the `rewind` command (not `resume`), when rewinding a session that is **still active** (session state file exists with a live `TranscriptPath`), the old code would use the exact known path. The new code uses `agent.ResolveSessionFile` which does a glob. For Claude, this is still deterministic (`<session-id>.jsonl`). For Gemini, it globs `session-*-<id[:8]>.json` and picks the alphabetically last match.\\n\\nFor **active sessions** on the same machine (no repo relocation), the old path from session state was more reliable — it was the actual path Gemini wrote to, not inferred via glob. The PR's approach is correct for the *relocation* scenario but is slightly weaker for the *active session on same machine* scenario when multiple Gemini sessions with the same short-ID prefix exist.\\n\\n**Git history context:** The `LoadSessionState` check was added in commit `a790770a` (\\\"correct id, but still wrong path. now it's working\\\") specifically to fix a Gemini session path resolution bug. Then `ff140f8f` made it public as `ResolveSessionFilePath`. The PR removes this as it conflicts with the location-independence goal, but it's worth being aware this is a deliberate trade-off.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Issue 5: `resolveTranscriptPath` in `rewind.go` Was Moved to `transcript.go` — Potential Visibility Issue\\n\\n**Severity: Low**\\n\\nThe commit `19aa9184` (\\\"review bugbotfeedback\\\") moved `resolveTranscriptPath` from `rewind.go` to `transcript.go`, apparently in response to a code review comment. However, both `rewind.go` and `debug.go` (line 363: `transcriptPath, err := resolveTranscriptPath(sessionID, ag)`) are in the same package `cli`, so this is fine functionally. The move is cosmetically appropriate since `transcript.go` groups transcript-related utilities.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Summary\\n\\n| Issue | Severity | File |\\n|---|---|---|\\n| `SanitizePathForGemini` → SHA256 breaks lookup of pre-existing Gemini sessions | **High** | `geminicli/gemini.go` |\\n| Stale comment \\\"Delegates to strategy.ResolveSessionFilePath\\\" | Low | `transcript.go:262` |\\n| Immediate field removal compresses explicit two-step deprecation from `91b70575` | Medium | `checkpoint/checkpoint.go` |\\n| `LoadSessionState` TranscriptPath check removed — weaker for active Gemini sessions | Medium | `strategy/manual_commit_rewind.go` |\\n\\nThe most significant concern from the history is Issue 1: the `SanitizePathForGemini` → SHA256 change is correct going forward (matches actual Gemini CLI source), but Gemini users who ran sessions with the old code will have their historical session files stored at a path the new code will never look in. The PR adds no migration path for this. The `ResolveSessionFile` glob (`session-*-<id[:8]>.json`) only helps within the right directory — if `GetSessionDir` now retur