gement\\n    18→- `entire/cli/integration_test`: integration tests\\n    19→\\n    20→## Tech Stack\\n    21→\\n    22→- Language: Go 1.25.x\\n    23→- Build tool: mise, go modules\\n    24→- Linting: golangci-lint\\n    25→\\n    26→## Development\\n    27→\\n    28→### Running Tests\\n    29→```bash\\n    30→mise run test\\n    31→```\\n    32→\\n    33→### Running Integration Tests\\n    34→```bash\\n    35→mise run test:integration\\n    36→```\\n    37→\\n    38→### Running All Tests (CI)\\n    39→```bash\\n    40→mise run test:ci\\n    41→```\\n    42→\\n    43→Integration tests use the `//go:build integration` build tag and are located in `cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/`.\\n    44→\\n    45→### Linting\\n    46→```bash\\n    47→mise run lint\\n    48→```\\n    49→\\n    50→## Code Patterns\\n    51→\\n    52→### Error Handling\\n    53→\\n    54→The CLI uses a specific pattern for error output to avoid duplication between Cobra and main.go.\\n    55→\\n    56→**How it works:**\\n    57→- `root.go` sets `SilenceErrors: true` globally - Cobra never prints errors\\n    58→- `main.go` prints errors to stderr, unless the error is a `SilentError`\\n    59→- Commands return `NewSilentError(err)` when they've already printed a custom message\\n    60→\\n    61→**When to use `SilentError`:**\\n    62→Use `NewSilentError()` when you want to print a custom, user-friendly error message instead of the raw error:\\n    63→\\n    64→```go\\n    65→// In a command's RunE function:\\n    66→if _, err := paths.RepoRoot(); err != nil {\\n    67→    cmd.SilenceUsage = true  // Don't show usage for prerequisite errors\\n    68→    fmt.Fprintln(cmd.ErrOrStderr(), \\\"Not a git repository. Please run 'entire enable' from within a git repository.\\\")\\n    69→    return NewSilentError(errors.New(\\\"not a git repository\\\"))\\n    70→}\\n    71→```\\n    72→\\n    73→**When NOT to use `SilentError`:**\\n    74→For normal errors where the default error message is sufficient, just return the error directly. main.go will print it:\\n    75→\\n    76→```go\\n    77→// Normal error - main.go will print \\\"unknown strategy: foo\\\"\\n    78→return fmt.Errorf(\\\"unknown strategy: %s\\\", name)\\n    79→```\\n    80→\\n    81→**Key files:**\\n    82→- `errors.go` - Defines `SilentError` type and `NewSilentError()` constructor\\n    83→- `root.go` - Sets `SilenceErrors: true` on root command\\n    84→- `main.go` - Checks for `SilentError` before printing\\n    85→\\n    86→### Git Operations\\n    87→\\n    88→We use github.com/go-git/go-git for most git operations, but with important exceptions:\\n    89→\\n    90→#### go-git v5 Bugs - Use CLI Instead\\n    91→\\n    92→**Do NOT use go-git v5 for `checkout` or `reset --hard` operations.**\\n    93→\\n    94→go-git v5 has a bug where `worktree.Reset()` with `git.HardReset` and `worktree.Checkout()` incorrectly delete untracked directories even when they're listed in `.gitignore`. This would destroy `.entire/` and `.worktrees/` directories.\\n    95→\\n    96→Use the git CLI instead:\\n    97→```go\\n    98→// WRONG - go-git deletes ignored directories\\n    99→worktree.Reset(&git.ResetOptions{\\n   100→    Commit: hash,\\n   101→    Mode:   git.HardReset,\\n   102→})\\n   103→\\n   104→// CORRECT - use git CLI\\n   105→cmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, \\\"git\\\", \\\"reset\\\", \\\"--hard\\\", hash.String())\\n   106→```\\n   107→\\n   108→See `HardResetWithProtection()` in `common.go` and `CheckoutBranch()` in `git_operations.go` for examples.\\n   109→\\n   110→Regression tests in `hard_reset_test.go` verify this behavior - if go-git v6 fixes this issue, those tests can be used to validate switching back.\\n   111→\\n   112→#### Repo Root vs Current Working Directory\\n   113→\\n   114→**Always use repo root (not `os.Getwd()`) when working with git-relative paths.**\\n   115→\\n   116→Git commands like `git status` and `worktree.Status()` return paths relative to the **repository root**, not the current working directory. When Gemini runs from a subdirectory (e.g., `/repo/frontend`), using `os.Getwd()` to construct absolute paths will produce incorrect results for files in sibling directories.\\n   117→\\n   118→```go\\n   119→// WRONG - breaks when running from subdirectory\\n   120→cwd, _ := os.Getwd()  // e.g., /repo/frontend\\n   121→absPath := filepath.Join(cwd, file)  // file=\\\"api/src/types.ts\\\" → /repo/frontend/api/src/types.ts (WRONG)\\n   122→\\n   123→// CORRECT - use repo root\\n   124→repoRoot, _ := paths.RepoRoot()  // or strategy.GetWorktreePath()\\n   125→absPath := filepath.Join(repoRoot, file)  // → /repo/api/src/types.ts (CORRECT)\\n   126→```\\n   127→\\n   128→This also affects path filtering. The `paths.ToRelativePath()` function rejects paths starting with `..`, so computing relative paths from cwd instead of repo root will filter out files in sibling directories:\\n   129→\\n   130→```go\\n   131→// WRONG - filters out sibling directory files\\n   132→cwd, _ := os.Getwd()  // /repo/frontend\\n   133→relPath := paths.ToRelativePath(\\\"/repo/api/file.ts\\\", cwd)  // returns \\\"\\\" (filtered out as \\\"../api/file.ts\\\")\\n   134→\\n   135→// CORRECT - keeps all repo files\\n   136→repoRoot, _ := paths.RepoRoot()\\n   137→relPath := paths.ToRelativePath(\\\"/repo/api/file.ts\\\", repoRoot)  // returns \\\"api/file.ts\\\"\\n   138→```\\n   139→\\n   140→**When to use `os.Getwd()`:** Only when you actually need the current directory (e.g., finding agent session directories that are cwd-relative).\\n   141→\\n   142→**When to use repo root:** Any time you're working with paths from git status, git diff, or any git-relative file list.\\n   143→\\n   144→Test case in `state_test.go`: `TestFilterAndNormalizePaths_SiblingDirectories` documents this bug pattern.\\n   145→\\n   146→### Session Strategies (`cmd/entire/cli/strategy/`)\\n   147→\\n   148→The CLI uses a strategy pattern for managing session data and checkpoints. Each strategy implements the `Strategy` interface defined in `strategy.go`.\\n   149→\\n   150→#### Core Interface\\n   151→All strategies implement:\\n   152→- `SaveStep()` - Save session step checkpoint (code + metadata)\\n   153→- `SaveTaskStep()` - Save subagent task step checkpoint\\n   154→- `GetRewindPoints()` / `Rewind()` - List and restore to checkpoints\\n   155→- `GetSessionLog()` / `GetSessionInfo()` - Retrieve session data\\n   156→- `ListSessions()` / `GetSession()` - Session discovery\\n   157→\\n   158→#### Available Strategies\\n   159→\\n   160→| Strategy | Main Branch | Metadata Storage | Use Case |\\n   161→|----------|-------------|------------------|----------|\\n   162→| **manual-commit** (default) | Unchanged (no commits) | `entire/<HEAD-hash>` branches + `entire/checkpoints/v1` | Recommended for most workflows |\\n   163→| **auto-commit** | Creates clean commits | Orphan `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch | Teams that want code commits from sessions |\\n   164→\\n   165→Legacy names `shadow` and `dual` are only recognized when reading settings or checkpoint metadata.\\n   166→\\n   167→#### Strategy Details\\n   168→\\n   169→**Manual-Commit Strategy** (`manual_commit*.go`) - Default\\n   170→- **Does not modify** the active branch - no commits created on the working branch\\n   171→- Creates shadow branch `entire/<HEAD-commit-hash>` per base commit for checkpoints\\n   172→- Session logs are condensed to permanent `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch on user commits\\n   173→- Builds git trees in-memory using go-git plumbing APIs\\n   174→- Rewind restores files from shadow branch commit tree (does not use `git reset`)\\n   175→- Tracks session state in `.git/entire-sessions/` (shared across worktrees)\\n   176→- PrePush hook can push `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch alongside user pushes\\n   177→- `AllowsMainBranch() = true` - safe to use on main/master since it never modifies commit history\\n   178→\\n   179→**Auto-Commit Strategy** (`auto_commit.go`)\\n   